 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#242422><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=quirtevans>QuirtEvans</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:yellow;'>Tavern Ale Swiller</span></span><br>  Posts: 75<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(5/19/03 1:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3251.topic&index=77>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wow...</span><hr size=1> I often agree with you Novbre, but not this time.<br>
<br>
First, let's not get caught up in the gun control argument, which goes on and on and on and on and on ....  I understand what you are saying, but for the sake of completeness, there is another side to the argument.  The constitutional amendment speaking about the right to keep and bear arms says:<br>
<br>
&quot;A well-regulated Militia being necessary to the security of a free State, the right of the people to keep and bear Arms shall not be infringed.&quot; <br>
<br>
In other words, the reason the right to keep and bear arms was guaranteed was for the express purpose of ensuring the continued availability of a well-regulated militia.<br>
<br>
The amendment, which was adopted in the 18th century, dealt with societal conditions at the time.  Things have changed since then.  First of all, at the time, if there was an Indian (sorry, to be politically correct, native American) uprising, you needed a gun to protect yourself because the nearest help was often days away, and there was no way to contact the authorities if you were under attack.  Not quite the same state of affairs today.<br>
<br>
Also, at the time, it wasn't really possible to carry a concealed, multiple shot weapon.  Guns were big, they were bulky, and Mr. Colt hadn't invented the revolver yet.  A single handgun simply couldn't do the damage then that it does now.  One could even argue, given the &quot;militia&quot; language on which the amendment is based, that the drafters of the constitution didn't have handguns in mind at all.  They could have thought &quot;arms&quot; meant rifles.  Single shot rifles, not automatic weapons, Uzis, or grenade launchers.  Or do you think that right to &quot;keep and bear Arms&quot; means that the government is constitutionally prohibited from passing a law barring you owning a rocket launcher?  Or a nuclear missile?    <br>
<br>
But let's put gun control aside, because we were talking about free speech.  Do you seriously think that, compared to 50 or 100 or 150 years ago, speech is less free today?  Anyone ever told you about the sedition laws?  Do you think that it was always possible to be an open member of the Communist party without getting thrown in jail?  <br>
<br>
Let's get to those CD lyrics.  You think that 50 or 75 years ago, obscene lyrics would have been tolerated?  Did you know that Cole Porter was basically forced to change the lyrics of one of his songs (&quot;I get no kick from cocaine&quot; became &quot;I get no kick from champagne&quot;) because the reference to drugs was deemed societally unacceptable?  When &quot;West Side Story&quot; was made into a movie, &quot;Gee Officer Krupke, fuck you!&quot; (the original language of the song) was required to be changed to &quot;Gee Officer Krupke, Krup you!&quot;  Do you think that would happen today?  (That was around 1960, give or take a couple of years.)<br>
<br>
Ever hear of book burning?  When a town decided they didn't like the sorts of books that the library was shelving, they just grabbed them off the shelf and burned them in a big barrel.  Ever hear of censorship, where certain books were not allowed to be brought into the country?  Tell me, do you really think that was more free than a silly little warning label?<br>
<br>
Or move on to cinema.  Do you happen to remember when people like Larry Flynt and Harry Reems were criminally prosecuted for obscenity?  It really wasn't that long ago, maybe 30 years.  When was the last time you heard about a criminal prosecution for obscenity (child pornography aside)?<br>
<br>
Moving away from free speech, you think people had more rights 100 or 150 years ago?  Back when people of a different skin color were slaves?  Back when women weren't allowed to vote?  How about 60 years ago or so, when people of Japanese ancestry were locked up in internment camps during World War II.  Did we do that to people of Iraqi descent in the last year?  Let's reel it in to only 50 years ago.  Back when, in many parts of the United States, people of a different skin color weren't allowed to ride on the same part of the bus as the white folks?<br>
<br>
Let's get some perspective here.  Even though there are restrictions on many of your freedoms (you still can't shout &quot;fire!&quot; in a crowded theater), our freedoms are generally .. generally .. as well protected as they have ever been in the history of this country.  Are there ways in which our rights could be better protected?  Probably.  But we've made progress in many ways over the course of time.  <br>
<br>
And basically, Morloc is right.  Freedoms can't be absolute, because if they are they will interfere with everyone else's freedoms.  Let's take the right to freedom of speech.  If you exercise your right to freedom of speech by using a bullhorn for hours on end in a crowded auditorium during a Presidential debate, you may be exercising your right to free speech, but you are interfering with the candidates' right to free speech, and you are interfering with everyone else's right to choose which speaker they want to listen to.  If you exercise your right to free speech by shouting &quot;I have a bomb and I'm going to blow this place up!&quot; in that same auditorium, there will be a stampede, people will die, and you will be interfering with those people's rights to life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness.  <br>
<br>
Inevitably, that's why there must be restrictions on freedoms, because rights bump into one another, and when they do something has to give.  <br>
<br>
If you think that's a slippery slope, maybe you're right.  But there is no way to create a place where the slope isn't slippery, or where someone's rights aren't trampled somehow.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub40.ezboard.com/bthesaryrntavern.showUserPublicProfile?gid=novbre>Novbre</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style='color:green;'>Tavern Patron</span></span><br>  Posts: 108<br> <font color=#6FB8DD>(5/19/03 7:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub40.ezboard.com/fthesaryrntavernthefurnace.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3251.topic&index=78>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/djimon/myhomepage/small%20sig%20final.jpg?mtbrand=AOL_US WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wow...</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>How long do you think it'd take for one person's &quot;freedom&quot; to begin interfering with another's?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
