Guess what? Congress has decided to backburner the renewal of the ban on semiautomatic assault rifles. It's slated to expire next year, and so far it doesn't appear very many people in congress are worried about it either. <br>
<br>
I watched a very interesting report on CNN, of course if you are an NRA member you may already know alot of this info. <br>
<br>
I will use as an example the AR15(The illegal model) and the AR15(legal model). There are very subtle differences, such as the illegal model has the flash supressor, the bayonet mount, magazines that carry over 10 rounds, and a foldable stock. <br>
<br>
Anyway, they both use a .223 projectile round, that causes the exact same impact, the features that make the one illegal are merely cosmetic and provide no more danger to anyone than the legal version does. Thus, why is one legal and the other not? Basically someone was ill-informed about the weapon and thus made a rash decision. <br>
<br>
Also, the statistics shown  to congress apparently has changed their outlook. Of all violent crimes that were commited since the ban went in to effect in 1994, I think it was only somthing like 40% of those used any kind of firearm. <br>
<br>
Glad to see congress actually looking at the facts rather than uninformed opinions of biased liberals who know nothing about guns or the people who own them. <br>
